I&#x27;m surprised I haven&#x27;t seen anybody mention the &quot;public final fields&quot; approach yet. I use this myself for immutable objects and I quite like it. Granted, you still need to implement equals and hashcode, but these can be generated easily and verified with tools like EqualsVerifier [2].<p>[1]<p><pre><code>  public class MyImmutable {
    public final String field1;
    public final int field2;

    public MyImmutable(String field1, int field2) {
        // assign
    }

     // equals, hashcode, toString
  }
</code></pre>
[2] <a href="https://github.com/jqno/equalsverifier" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/jqno/equalsverifier</a>

I think people use DI just because Java constructor syntax is so incredibly verbose:<p><pre><code>    public class MyClass {
      @Inject private String foo;
    }
</code></pre>
versus<p><pre><code>    public class MyClass {
      private String foo;

      @Inject public MyClass(String foo) {
        this.foo = foo;
      }
    }</code></pre>
